  "prompt": "Is there some scientific proof that Jesus who's a real person or just mythology figure",
  "response": "The question of whether Jesus was a real historical figure or a mythological one is a topic of ongoing debate among scholars. Here is a summary of the main arguments and evidence:\n\n### Historical Evidence:\n\n1. **Non-Christian Sources:**\n   - **Tacitus (Roman Historian):** In his work \"Annals,\" Tacitus mentions \"Christus\" who suffered under Pontius Pilate during the reign of Tiberius. This is considered a key non-Christian reference to Jesus.\n   - **Josephus (Jewish Historian):** In his \"Antiquities of the Jews,\" Josephus refers to Jesus as a wise man who was crucified under Pilate. Although the passage has been debated for possible Christian interpolations, most scholars believe the core of the text is authentic.\n   - **Pliny the Younger (Roman Governor):** In his letters to Emperor Trajan, Pliny mentions early Christians and their worship of Christ.\n\n2. **Christian Sources:**\n   - **The New Testament:** The Gospels and epistles of the New Testament provide detailed accounts of Jesus' life, teachings, death, and resurrection. While these are religious texts, they are considered primary sources by historians.\n   - **Early Church Fathers:** Writers like Clement of Rome, Ignatius of Antioch, and Polycarp of Smyrna, who lived in the 1st and 2nd centuries, refer to Jesus as a historical figure.\n\n### Scholarly Consensus:\n\nMost historians and scholars of religion agree that Jesus of Nazareth was a real historical figure. The consensus is that he was a Jewish teacher and healer who was crucified in Jerusalem during the reign of Tiberius under the governance of Pontius Pilate. This view is supported by both Christian and non-Christian sources.\n\n### Mythological Aspects:\n\nSome scholars argue that elements of the Jesus story may have mythological or legendary aspects. These include:\n- **Miraculous Birth and Resurrection:** These are common themes in many mythologies and religions.\n- **Comparisons with Other Figures:** Some scholars point out similarities between Jesus and other mythological figures, such as the Egyptian god Osiris or the Greek god Dionysus.\n\n### The Mythicist View:\n\nA minority view known as \"mythicism\" posits that Jesus was not a historical figure but a purely mythological construct. Proponents of this view, such as Earl Doherty and Richard Carrier, argue that the earliest Christian writings do not necessarily refer to a historical Jesus and that the story of Jesus evolved from earlier myths.\n\n### Conclusion:\n\nWhile there is a scholarly consensus that Jesus was a real historical figure, debates continue about the nature and extent of the historical evidence, as well as the mythological aspects of his story. The historicity of Jesus is supported by a range of sources, but interpretations of these sources vary.\n\nIf you're interested in delving deeper, here are some recommended readings:\n- **\"The Historical Jesus: The Life of a Mediterranean Jewish Peasant\" by John Dominic Crossan**\n- **\"Jesus: Apocalyptic Prophet of the New Millennium\" by Bart D. Ehrman**\n- **\"On the Historicity of Jesus: Why We Might Have Reason for Doubt\" by Richard Carrier**\n\nThese works represent different perspectives on the historicity of Jesus and can provide a more comprehensive understanding of the ongoing scholarly discussions.",
